{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11969"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11969"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0.15,0.04,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68000"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being thrown from his motorcycle. He has removed his helmet and reports neck pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is alert and oriented with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 15. He is ambulant but keeping his head still due to pain. Cervical spine precautions are in place. There are superficial abrasions on his right arm. He has tenderness on palpation of the posterior midline of his neck. Neurological examination of his upper and lower limbs is normal. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis breath alcohol reading performed in the Emergency Department is 0.00.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is NOT included in the NEXUS criteria for cervical spine imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intoxication with alcohol or drugs","Posterior midline cervical tenderness","Distracting injury elsewhere","Neurological deficit","Active neck rotation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe NEXUS (National Emergency X-Radiography Utilization Study) criteria is a validated clinical decision tool used to determine the need for cervical spine imaging in trauma patients under 60 years of age. It has a sensitivity of 99.6% for clinically significant cervical spine injury. The criteria can be remembered using the mnemonic NSAID: neurological deficit, spinal tenderness, altered consciousness, intoxication, and distracting injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive neck rotation\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the NEXUS criteria. In fact, active range of motion testing should never be performed until cervical spine injury has been excluded through either the NEXUS criteria or appropriate imaging, as this could potentially worsen an unstable injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntoxication with alcohol or drugs\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the five NEXUS criteria as intoxicated patients may have an unreliable examination and may not appropriately report symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior midline cervical tenderness\u003C/strong\u003E is another NEXUS criterion as it directly suggests underlying bony, ligamentous or soft tissue injury. This requires careful palpation of the posterior midline structures from the occiput to C7.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistracting injury elsewhere\u003C/strong\u003E is included in NEXUS and refers to any injury producing pain sufficient to draw attention away from a cervical spine injury, such as long bone fractures, large lacerations, or significant burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurological deficit\u003C/strong\u003E is also part of NEXUS and includes any new motor weakness, sensory loss, or reflex changes that may indicate spinal cord injury or nerve root compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf any of the NEXUS criteria are present, cervical spine imaging is mandatory. Only when all criteria are absent can cervical spine imaging be safely omitted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The NEXUS criteria is a validated clinical decision tool to determine the need for cervical spine imaging in trauma patients under 60 years.","The five NEXUS criteria are: neurological deficit, spinal tenderness, altered consciousness, intoxication, and distracting injury.","Active range of motion testing should not be performed before cervical spine injury has been excluded."],"references":["Hoffman JR, Mower WR, Wolfson AB, Todd KH, Zucker MI. Validity of a set of clinical criteria to rule out injury to the cervical spine in patients with blunt trauma. National Emergency X-Radiography Utilization Study Group. N Engl J Med. 2000 Jul 13;343(2):94-9. doi: 10.1056/NEJM200007133430203. Erratum in: N Engl J Med 2001 Feb 8;344(6):464. PMID: 10891516."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68000"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11969"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68000"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T17:57:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T17:57:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82911"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4961"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms"